# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The **1920 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau during one month from January 5, 1920, determined the resident population of the United States to be 106,021,537, an increase of 15.0 percent over the 92,228,496 persons enumerated during the 1910 census.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The 1920 Census was determined for 1 January 1920.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The actual date of the enumeration appears on the heading of each page of the census schedule, but all responses were to reflect the individual's status as of 1 January, even if the status had changed between 1 January and the day of enumeration.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] In 1929, Congress passed the Reapportionment Act of 1929 which provided for a permanent method of reapportionment and fixed the number of representatives at 435.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the United States recorded a population of more than 100 million.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which a state—New York—recorded a population of more than ten million.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] This census also marked a significant population shift from rural to urban.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, "Beginning in 1910, the minimum population threshold to be categorized as an urban place was set at 2,500.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] 'Urban' was defined as including all territory, persons, and housing units within an incorporated area that met the population threshold.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1920 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1920.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1920 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1920 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 2, 1920, as part of the 1920 United States presidential election which was held throughout all contemporary 48 states.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Voters chose 9 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for the Democratic nominee, Governor James M.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Cox of Ohio, over Republican nominee, Senator Warren G.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Cox ran with Assistant Secretary of the Navy Franklin D.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Roosevelt of New York, while Harding ran with Governor Calvin Coolidge of Massachusetts.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Cox won South Carolina by a landslide margin of 92.14%.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1920-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] In the midst of a massive nationwide Republican landslide, South Carolina was a staggering 118.3% more Democratic than the national average.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1924 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 4, 1924, as part of the 1924 United States presidential election which was held throughout all contemporary 48 states.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for the Democratic nominee, Ambassador John W.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Davis of West Virginia, over the Republican nominee, incumbent President Calvin Coolidge of Massachusetts.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Bryan of Nebraska, while Coolidge ran with former Budget Director Charles G.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Also running in this election was the Progressive Party nominee, Senator Robert M.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] La Follette of Wisconsin and his running mate Senator Burton K.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1924-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Davis won South Carolina by a wide margin of 94.35 percentage points.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1928 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 6, 1928, as part of the 1928 United States presidential election which was held throughout all contemporary 48 states.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for the Democratic nominee, Governor Alfred E.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Smith of New York, over the Republican nominee, former Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover of California.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Smith ran with Senator Joseph Taylor Robinson of Arkansas, while Hoover's running mate was Senate Majority Leader Charles Curtis of Kansas.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] In the midst of a third Republican landslide, Smith won South Carolina by a margin of 82.85%.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Not only was South Carolina Al Smith's best state, it was the largest margin of victory by both Al Smith and Herbert Hoover that year, largely accredited to Southern politics being heavily Democratic and low voter turnout.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1928-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The sheer scale of the state's disfranchisement meant that Smith won every county in the state, which he was unable to do even in Mississippi.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] The **1930 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau one month from April 1, 1930, determined the resident population of the United States to be 122,775,046, an increase of 13.7 percent over the 106,021,537 persons enumerated during the 1920 census.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] It was the first time the effects of suburban sprawl were recorded when, during the Roaring Twenties, a significant portion of the working population of New York City moved to New Jersey, aided by the George Washington Bridge which permitted quick transport from the state to Manhattan.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] It was also the first in which a city in the Western United States (Los Angeles) reached a population of at least a million people.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1930 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in 1949, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is located on 2,667 rolls of microfilm, and available from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1930 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1930-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1930.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1932 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 8, 1932, as part of the 1932 United States presidential election which was held throughout all contemporary 48 states.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Voters chose 8 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for the Democratic nominee, Governor Franklin D.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Roosevelt of New York, over the Republican nominee, incumbent President Herbert Hoover of California.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Roosevelt ran with incumbent Speaker of the House John Nance Garner of Texas, while Hoover's running mate was incumbent Vice President Charles Curtis of Kansas.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Roosevelt won South Carolina almost unanimously, taking 98.03% of the vote to Hoover's 1.89%.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] He swept every county in the state with more than 80% of the vote, and all but one (historically Black Republican leaning Beaufort County) with greater than 90%.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1932-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] With a victory margin of 96.14%, South Carolina proved to be Roosevelt's strongest state in this election.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1936 United States presidential election in South Carolina** was held on November 3, 1936.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state voters chose 8 electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] With Roosevelt winning 98.57% of the vote, this was the most emphatic win for any presidential candidate in a contested election for any state in American history.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for Democratic Party candidate and incumbent President Franklin D.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Roosevelt over Republican Party candidate incumbent Governor of Kansas Alf Landon.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Roosevelt carried all counties with over 90% of the vote and all but one (historically Black Republican leaning Beaufort County) with over 95% of the vote, with two (Horry and Lancaster counties) being carried unanimously.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] His 98.57% of the popular vote is the highest for any presidential candidate in South Carolina since a popular vote was first used in 1868, or for any presidential candidate in any state with an opponent.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] At the time of the 1936 election, the Democratic machine had been dominant in South Carolina politics for decades.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state's Republican organizations were marginal, serving mostly to distribute patronage when a Republican president made federal appointments within the state.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The South Carolina Republican Party had been led by "Tieless" Joe Tolbert since the late 1890s.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] However, in the early 1930s, the state party split between two factions: a racially exclusive all-white group led by J.C.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Hambright, and Tolbert's group, which included some African-Americans.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] At the 1932 Republican National Convention, Hambright was seated as the leader of South Carolina's delegation, but at the 1936 convention, Tolbert's authority was restored.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The schism between the two Republican factions extended to the 1936 presidential ballot.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] At that time, voters were presented with lists of electors nominated by each state party, rather than the names of the presidential and vice-presidential candidates themselves.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] As a result, two separate slates of Republican electors were nominated, one led by Hambright and the other by Tolbert's nephew Joseph A.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Tolbert, and the state's already minuscule Republican vote was split between them.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] However, ballots in Allendale County, Colleton County, and Edgefield County counties listed only the Tolbert ticket as the slate of the Republican Party.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/1936-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The votes for Landon are presented here as a fusion of the two slates.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale County was formed in 1919 from southwestern portions of Barnwell County, along the Savannah River, and part of Hampton County, just to its south.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] It is the location of the Topper Site, an archeological excavation providing possible evidence of a pre-Clovis culture dating back 50,000 years.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The site is near a source of chert on private land in Martin owned by Clariant Corporation, a Swiss chemical company with a plant there.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The site, named after David Topper, has been under excavation by archeologists from the University of South Carolina for about one month a year since 1999, after an initial exploratory dig in the mid-1980s.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale County was born out of a desire for convenience.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Having a new county circumvented the need to travel to the courthouse in Barnwell or Hampton.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The original Allendale County Courthouse burned down in May 1998, with reconstruction begun in August 2002.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] During the Civil Rights movement, the Courthouse almost became a site for a sit-in protest after African-American citizens charged officials with deliberately delaying the voter registration of Black residents.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The Savannah River forms the county's western border with Georgia.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale is 62 miles (100 km) from Augusta, Georgia; 73 miles (117 km) from Savannah, Georgia; 87 miles (140 km) from Columbia; and 90 miles (140 km) from Charleston.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Before interstate highways were built, Allendale had several motels, primarily serving travelers in-between Northeastern states and Florida.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Traffic that formerly traveled US 301 through Allendale now uses Interstate 95.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 8,039, 3,281 households, and 1,389 families.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The median age was 47.2 years, with medians of 51.4 for women and 44.5 for men; 16.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 22.8% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 112.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 114.0 males age 18 and over.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] 0.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 100.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] There were 3,281 households in the county, of which 23.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 43.6% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] About 39.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 18.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] There were 4,040 housing units, exceeding the number of households and of which 18.8% were vacant; among occupied units 64.4% were owner-occupied and 35.6% were renter-occupied.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.8% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%, while the median household size was 2 (with a mean of 2.2).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] At the 2010 census, there were 10,419 people, 3,706 households, and 2,333 families living in the county.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The population density was 25.5 inhabitants per square mile (9.8/km2).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] There were 4,486 housing units at an average density of 11.0 per square mile (4.2/km2).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 73.6% Black or African American, 23.7% white, 0.4% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 1.3% from other races, and 0.8% from two or more races.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 2.3% of the population.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] In terms of ancestry, and 5.6% were American.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Of the 3,706 households, 32.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 31.5% were married couples living together, 26.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 37.0% were non-families, and 33.7% of households were made up of individuals.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 3.14.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The median household income was $20,081 and the median family income was $25,146.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $30,440 versus $28,889 for females.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $14,190.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] About 35.7% of families and 42.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 53.8% of those under age 18 and 27.4% of those age 65 or over.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] At the 2000 census, there were 11,211 people, 3,915 households, and 2,615 families living in the county.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The population density was 28 people per square mile (11 people/km2).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] There were 4,568 housing units at an average density of 11 per square mile (4.2/km2).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 71.0 percent Black or African American, 27.37 percent White, 0.12 percent Asian, 0.09 percent Native American, 0.06 percent Pacific Islander, 0.85 percent from other races, and 0.51 percent from two or more races.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] 1.61 percent of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Of the 3,915 households, 30.3 percent had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.8 percent were married couples living together, 25.8 percent had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.2 percent were non-families.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] 30.0 percent of all households were one person and 12.3 percent had someone living alone who was 65 or older.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.56 and the average family size was 3.21.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The age distribution was 26.6 percent under the age of 18, 9.8 percent from 18 to 24, 28.2 percent from 25 to 44, 22.8 percent from 45 to 64, and 12.7 percent who were 65 or older.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 108.6 males.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 107.5 males.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The median household income was $20,898 and the median family income was $27,348.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $25,930 versus $20,318 for females.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $11,293.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] About 28.4 percent of families and 34.5 percent of the population were below the poverty line, including 48.1 percent of those under age 18 and 26.00 percent of those age 65 or over.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale County has a five-member council elected from single-member districts.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Leading up to the 2020 Census Redistricting, Allendale County was divided between Senate districts 40 (the eastern half) and 45 (the western half).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Senate District 40 has been represented by Democrat and Minority Leader Brad Hutto since 1996.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Democrat Margie Bright Matthews has represented District 45 since 2015, after she was elected to the position to fulfill the unexpired term of Clementa C.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Following the redistricting, which will be used in the 2024 United States elections despite legal disputes over racial and political gerrymandering, Allendale County is solely covered by state Senate District 40.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale County has been consistently Democratic in Presidential voting since 1976 and was among the few counties to be carried by Walter Mondale in 1984.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] In the 2008 U.S. presidential election Barack Obama received 75.3 percent of the county's vote.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] In the 2012 U.S. presidential election Barack Obama received 79.2 percent of the county's vote.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] In the 2020 U.S. presidential election, Joe Biden received 75.6% of the vote.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] In 2024, the county saw a slight rightward shift, but it was still by far the most Democratic county in the state of South Carolina in that election.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale is primarily an agricultural rural county.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Its primary products are cotton, soybeans, watermelon and cantaloupe.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Timbering is also important, primarily for paper pulp.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] In chained 2017 dollars, its real GDP was $240.4 million (approx. $29,902 per capita).
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] From 2021 through 2024, its unemployment rate has fluctuated between 4-8%.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] As of April 2024, some of the largest employers in the county include Atlantic Power Corporation, AZ Electronic Materials, Georgia-Pacific, South Carolina Department of Corrections (SCDC), and the University of South Carolina.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The county is also the site of WEBA, Channel 14, a broadcast outlet of the South Carolina Educational Television Network.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Ranking 45th in population among the state's 46 counties, it is the smallest county to have either a state-supported college or an ETV station.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] There is one school district: Allendale County School District.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Allendale County School District includes one high school: Allendale-Fairfax High School.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] Bing High School served African-American students until desegregation.
[src:allendale-county-south-carolina/allendale-county-south-carolina] The last local news publications, *The Citizen-Leader* and *The Allendale Sun*, stopped printing in 2014 and 2015, respectively.
